Discrete probability models

Discrete probability models

A mass probability function of a discrete random variable X with possible values \(x_1 , x_2 , .. , x_m\) is any function such that

  • \(f(x_i)\geq 0\)
  • \(\sum_{i=1}^m f(x_i)=1\)
  • \(f(x_i)=P(X=x_i)\)

They are abstract objects with general properties that may or may not describe a natural or engineered process.

Discrete probability models

Discrete probability models are probability mass functions that we believe describe processes like real random experiments.

Analogy: Think of the function \(f(x,y)=x^2+y^2\)

  • \(f(x,y)=a^2\) is a circle of radius \(a\).
  • it is an abstract object.
  • it represents the shape of many real objects.
  • the shape of real objects is an approximation of the circle.

Discrete probability models

Discrete random models are functions that are idealizations of random experiments on discrete variables.

  • What is the simplest model?

Discrete probability models

The classical interpretation of probability (Laplace)

Whenever a sample space consists of N possible events that are equally likely, the probability of each outcome is \(\frac{1}{N}\).

On many occasions:

  • we can reason the possible values that a random variable can take.

  • we have no reason to suppose that one outcome is more probable than the other.

Uniform distribution

Think of a dice or the lottery:

  • we can count all possible outcomes (dice:1-6, lottery:0000-9999)

  • we have a strong belief that they all are equally probable (dice: \(1/6\), lottery: \(10^{-4}\)) because the game is fair and before the game, we are completely ignorant of the outcome!

Uniform distribution

Definition A random variable X has a discrete uniform distribution if each of the n values in its range, say, has equal probability. Then, \(f(x)=\frac{1}{n}\)

plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-1

Uniform distribution

  • If \(f(x)\) for \(x\in\{a, a+1, ...b\}\), where \(a\) and \(b\) are integer, the size of the sample space is: \(n=b-a+1\)

  • If all the the events are equally probable then \[f(x)=\frac{1}{b-a+1}\]

Uniform distribution

Let’s compute the mean of the uniform distribution.

  • changing variables for \(Y=X-a+1\), \(y\in\{1, 2, ...n\}\) then

\[f(y)=\frac{1}{n}\].

  • and the fact that \(\sum_{y=1}^n y = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}\)

then the mean \(E(Y)\), is given by

\(E(Y)\sum_{y=1}^n y\big(\frac{1}{n}\big)=\frac{n+1}{2}\)

and \(E(X)=E(Y+a-1)=\frac{n+1}{2}+a-1=\frac{(b-a+1)+1}{2}+a-1=\frac{b+a}{2}\)

Uniform distribution

The variance of \(Y\) is

\(V(Y) = E(Y^2)-E(Y)^2\)

\(= \sum_{y=1}^n y^2\big(\frac{1}{n}\big) -E(Y)^2\)

\(= \frac{1}{n}\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} -\big(\frac{n+1}{2}\big)^2\)

\(= \frac{n^2-1}{12}\)

because \(V(Y)=V(X)\) then \(V(X)=\frac{(b-a+1)^2-1}{12}\)

Uniform distribution

What is the mean and variance of a dice?

Sample space \(X\in\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}\) then \(n=6\)

  • \(E(X)=\frac{n+1}{2}=3.5\). Note that the expected value is not in the sample space! (is not a possible outcome)

  • \(V(X)=\frac{n^2-1}{12}=2.91\)

Bernoulli trials

The simplest case of a mass probability function is where there are two possible outcomes (\(A\) and \(B\)). If they are equally probable we have the flip of a coin.

  • let’s try to advance from the equal probability case and suppose that the outcomes have unequal probabilities

Bernoulli trials

What if we let them have different probabilities

  • outcome A (success): has probability \(p\)
  • outcome B (failure): has probability \(q=1-p\) (\(q+p=1\))

Then we define the random variable \(K\) (big \(K\)) where \(k=1\) (little \(k\)) when the observation is \(A\) and \(k=1\) abd \(k=0\) when the observation is \(B\).

Bernoulli trials

The probability mass function of \(K\) is \[ P(K=k)=f(k)= \begin{cases} q=1-p,& \text{if } k=0\, (event\, B)\\ p,& k=1\, (event\, A) \end{cases} \]

or more shortly

\(f(k)=(1-p)^{1-k} p^k\), for \(k=(0,1)\)

Bernoulli trials

Every time we have two different outcomes, where we can define a variable \(k=0\) for one outcome and \(k=1\) for the other.

We think of a Bernulli probability function \(f(k)=(1-p)^{1-k} p^k\).

  • In the uniform distribution, if we know the outcomes the mass probability distribution is fully known.

  • In a Bernoulli trial we allow ourselves the flexibility of not knowing the number \(p\) (the probability relationship between the outcomes).

Bernoulli trials

\(p\) is a parameter of the distribution: it is allowed to change.

  • Bernoulli trial is really a family of distributions
  • when we fix the value of \(p\) then we have a single probability mass function \(f(k;p)\).

Why do we let \(p\) free? because our hope is that data, the real observations, will tell us what its value is (from lecture 7 on estimation onwards).

Bernoulli trials

For the following lectures, we are going to assume we know the value of \(p\).

  • When we flip a coin then we “know” that \(A\):Tail\(\rightarrow k=1\) and \(B\):Head \(\rightarrow k=0\) have equall probabilities and therefore \(p=1/2\) and

\[f(k)=\frac{1}{2}^{1-k} \frac{1}{2}^k= \frac{1}{2}\].

  • If we assume that the probability of erroneously transmiting (\(k=1\)) one bit of information is \(p=1/10\) then if the correct transmission of the bit is \(k=0\), we have

\[f(k)=\frac{9}{10}^{1-k} \frac{1}{10}^k\]

Bernoulli trials

What is the mean and variance of \(f(k)=(1-p)^{1-k} p^k\)?

  • The mean \(E(K)= \sum_{k=0}^1 k f(k)=f(1)=p\)

  • The variance \(V(K)= \sum_{k=0}^1 (k-p)^2 f(k)\)

\(= p^2(1-p)+(1-p)^2p\)

\(= (1-p)(p^2 + p-p^2)\)

\(= (1-p)p = pq\)

Binomial distribution

Suppose that we are interested in learning about a particular Bernoulli trial.

  • We repat the Bernoulli trial \(n\) times and count how many times we obtained \(A\).

  • We define a random variable \(X\) such that it counts in \(n\) trials how many times we obtained the outcome \(A\). \(x \in {0,1,...n}\)

What is the probability of \(P(X=x)\)?

Binomial distribution

  • tossing a coin \(n\) times and counting the number of tails. What is the probability of observing \(x\) tails in \(n\) throws?

  • transmitting \(n\) bits and counting the number of errors, when the transmission of a single error is \(p\). What is the probability of observing \(x\) errors when transmitting \(n\) bits?

  • asking \(n\) people whether they will vote for the political party in government when the probability that someone votes for the ruling party is \(p\). What is the probability of observing \(x\) likely votes for the ruling party in \(n\) people?

Binomial distribution

  • each outcome \(A\) of a Bernoulli trial is observed with probability \(p\).
  • each outcome \(B\) (not \(A\)) of a Bernoulli trial is observed with probability \(1-p\).

Important! The random experiment here is the outcome of \(n\) independent random experiments (Bernoulli trials): the outcome is the sum of Bernoulli outcomes.

Binomial distribution

  • When we ask 100 people for their voting preferences we will get one \(x\), say 45; when we ask another 100 people we will get other \(x\) say 40; and so on…

Therefore every time we run a poll, we obtain a different \(x\), and then it makes sense to ask for the probability of \(x\) events \(P(X=x)\) when the probability that a single event is \(p\).

We want to find \(P(X=x)=f(x)\) in terms of \(p\).

Binomial distribution

What is the probability of observing \(3\) errors when transmitting \(4\) bits, when the probability of a single error is \(p\)?

  • Sampling space for one bit:

\(S=\{B:correct, A=error\}\)

Let’s assume that the probability of the event \(A\) \(A\) (error) is \(p\)

\(P(A)=p\)

\(P(B)=1-p\)

  • and define the random variable \(K\) for the transmission of one bit

\(K:\{B,A\} \rightarrow \{0,1\}\)

Binomial distribution

  • We then send 4 bits and count the number of errors in the transmission using the random variable \(X\). The possible results of the transmission are

\((0,0,0,0)\): X=0,
\((0,0,0,1)\): X=1,
\((0,0,1,0)\): X=1,
\((0,1,0,0)\): X=1,
\((1,0,0,0)\): X=1,
\((0,0,1,1)\): X=2,
\((0,1,0,1)\): X=2,
\((1,0,0,1)\): X=2,
\((0,1,1,0)\): X=2,
\((1,0,1,0)\): X=2,
\((1,1,0,0)\): X=2,
\((0,1,1,1)\): X=3,
\((1,0,1,1)\): X=3,
\((1,1,0,0)\): X=3,
\((1,1,1,0)\): X=3,
\((1,1,1,1)\): X=4

¿What are the probabilities for \(X=0,1,2,3,4\), when the probability of ontainig \(1\) (an error for a single bit) is \(p\)?

This time the results do not have the same probability!

Binomial distribution

In each tranmission there are 4 events; for instance we could have obtained:

\((1,1,0,1)=(A_1, A_2, B_3, A_4)\)

  • The bit number \(3\) was correcly transmitted (event \(B\))
  • The bits \(1\), \(2\) y \(4\) had errors (events \(A\))

If we assume that thre transmission of each event (bit) is independent of each other, then

\(P(1,1,0,1)=P(A_1)*P(A_2)*P(B_3)*P(A_4)\)

\(=p*p*(1-p)*p=(1-p)p^3\)

Note that we could have obtained 3 errors in the transmission

\((1,1,0,0)=(A_1, A_2, A_3, B_4)\) and that the probability is the same

\(P(1,1,1,0)=(1-p)p^3\)

Binomial distribution

What is the probability of observing 3 errors \(P(X=3)\)?

It will the the sim of the probabilities of having sent 3 errores from all possible transmissions.

errors 0 1 2 3
number of transmissions \(n_0=1\) \(n_1=4\) \(n_2=6\) \(n_3=4\)

We then have \(\binom 4 3 = 4\) possible ways of obtaining 3 errors, then

\(P(X=3)=f(3)=\binom 4 3 (1-p)p^3\)

es la suma de las probabilidades de cada una de estas 6 trasmisiones que dan lugar a 3 errores.

Binomial distribution

What is the probability of observing \(x\) errors when transmitting \(n\) bits, when the probability of a single error is \(p\)?

  • the probability that one transmission has \(x\) errors in \(n\) bits is \((1-p) ^ {n-x}p ^ x\)

  • \(x\) errors can be found in \(\binom n x\) different transmissions of \(n\) bits: The number of subsets of \(x\) elements from a set of \(n\) elements.

Therefore, the probability of observing the transmission event made on any \(x\) errors (single Bernoulli outcomes) is

\(f(x)=\binom n x p^x(1-p)^{n-x}\), \(x=0,1,...n\)

Binomial distribution

Definition

The binomial probability function is the probability mass function of observing \(x\) outcomes of type \(A\) in \(n\) independent Bernoulli trials, where \(A\) has the same probability \(p\) in each trial.

The function is given by

\(f(x)=\binom n x p^x(1-p)^{n-x}\), \(x=0,1,...n\)

When a variable \(X\) has a binomial probability function we say its distributes binomially and write

\(X\hookrightarrow Bin(n,p)\)

Binomial distribution

The mean of the binomial distribution requires some algera, but is result is simple and very intuitive.

\(E(X)= \sum_{x=0}^n\binom n x x(1-p)^{n-x} p^x\)
\(= \sum_{x=0}^n \frac{n!}{x! (n-x)!} x (1-p)^{n-x}p^x\)
\(= \sum_{x=0}^n \frac{n!}{(x-1)! (n-x)!} (1-p)^{n-x}p^x\)
\(= n\sum_{x=0}^n \frac{(n-1)!}{(x-1)! (n-1-(x-1)!)} (1-p)^{n-x}p^x\)
\(= n\,\, \sum_{x=0}^n \binom {n-1} {x-1} (1-p)^{n-x}p^x\)
\(= np\,\,\sum_{x=1}^n \binom {n-1} {x-1} (1-p)^{(n-1)-(x-1)}p^{x-1}\)
\(= np\,\, \sum_{x-1=0}^{n-1} f(x-1)= np\)

Binomial distribution

The mean and variance of \(X\hookrightarrow Bin(n,p)\) are

  • \(E(X)=np\)
  • \(V(X)=np(1-p)\)

For demonstrating the variance

  • we first find the result of \(E(X^2)=E(X(X-1))-E(X)=n(n-1)p^2 +np\)

  • and then use \(V(X)=E(X^2)-E(X)^2\)

Binomial distribution

  • The binomial distribution has two parameters: \(n\) and \(p\).

  • The expectation of runing multiple Bernulli trials and summing their results is the result of multiplying the expectation of a single Bernulli trial by \(n\):

\(E(X)=np\).

… so by tossing many times a coin, we can get to know the probability of a single tossing of the coin.

Binomial distribution

Let’s briefly jump ahead.

  • What if we replace \(E(X)\) by the result of a single \(n\)-trial experiment? If we observed \(x=n_{tail}\sim E(X)=np\)

  • then \(\frac{n_{tail}}{n} \sim p\).

  • We can get to know \(p\) from repeating an experiment!

Binomial distribution

Consider noisy channel where bits (0,1) are transmitted randomly with the same probability the mass probability function of transmitting \(k\) number of 1’s in a 4-bit transmission is

\(f(x)= \binom 4 x (\frac{1}{2})^4\)

# de errores x=0 x=1 x=2 x=3 x=4 total
\(f(x)\) \(1/16\) \(4/16\) \(6/16\) \(4/16\) \(1/16\) 1

Geometric distribution for events

  • Experiment: Suppose performing Bernoulli trials until we observe the first time the outcome A appears.

  • Random variable: We would like to count the number of \(B\)’s we obtained

  • Example: when tossing a coin until observing a tail

  • Question: What is the probability of tossing the coin \(k\) times until the first tail appears?

Geometric distribution for events

  • when transmitting bits and counting the number of bits transmitted until we find the first error if the transmission of a single error is \(p\):

What is the probability of sending \(k\) correct bits until the first error appears?

  • when asking people whether they will vote for the political party in government, if the probability that someone votes for the ruling party is \(p\):

What is the probability asking \(k\) times until finding the first person likely to vote for the ruling party?

Geometric distribution for events

Let’s compute the probability of transmitting bits with \(y\) number of bits correctly transmitted (\(B\)) and the last bit being an error (\(A\)); when the probability of an error is \(p\).

\((0,0,0,..0,1)=(B_1, B_2, B_3, B_y,A_y+1)\)

The probability of \(y\) events of type \(B\) is

\(P(0,0,0,..0,1)=P(Y=y)=f(y)=(1-p)^{y}p\)

(there is only one possible transmission for \(y\) number of correctly trasmitted bits)

Geometric distribution for events

The geometric distribution for the number of events \(B\) before an event \(A\) occurs is

\(P(Y=y)=f(y)=(1-p)^{y}p\), for \(y=0,1,2,...\)

and has

  • mean: \(E(Y)= \sum_{y=0}^\infty y(1-p)^{y}p=\frac{1-p}{p}\)

  • variance: \(V(Y)= \frac{1-p}{p^2}\)

Geometric distribution for events

Geometric distribution for events

Now, consider imagine that we would like to count the number of trials using the random varible \(M\)

\((0,0,0,..0,1)=(B_1, B_2, B_3, B_y,A_y+1)\)

The probability of observing \(m=y+1\) trials is the same probability of observing \(y\) correctly transmitted bits. We only need to change the variable

\(P(0,0,0,..0,1)=P(Y=y)=(1-p)^{y}p=(1-p)^{m-1}p=P(M=m)\)

Geometric distribution for trials es:

\(f(m)=(1-p)^{m-1}p,\), for \(m=1,2,3,...\)

with

  • mean: \(E(M)= \sum_{m=1}^\infty m(1-p)^{m-1}p=\frac{1}{p}\)

  • variance: \(V(M)= \frac{1-p}{p^2}\)

Note that \(y\) starts with 0, while \(m\) starts with \(1\).

Negative binomial distribution for events

Now let us imagine that we can be tolerant of a given number of errors in the signal transmission of bits. Say we can tolerate \(r\) errors in a transmission.

  • Experiment: Suppose performing Bernoulli trials until we observe the outcome \(A\) appears \(r\) times.

  • Random variable: We count the number of events \(B\)

  • Example: What is the probability of observing \(k\) well-transmitted (\(B\)) bits before \(r\) errors (\(A\))?

Negative binomial distribution for events

Let’s find first the probability of one particular transmission with \(y\) correct bits (\(B\)) and \(r\) errors (\(A\)).

\((0,0,1,., 0,1,...0,1)=(B_1, B_2, A_3, ..., B_i,A_{i+1}, ... B_{y+r-1},A_{y+r})\)

We observe \(y\) correct bits ins a total of \(y + r\) trials.

Then

  • \(P(0,0,1,., 0,1,...0,1)=(1-p)^yp^r\)

  • the last bit is fixed (marks the end of transmission)

  • The total number of transmisions with \(y\) number of correct bits (\(B\)) that we can obtain in \(y + r-1\) trials is: \(\binom {y + r-1} k\)

Negative binomial distribution for events

Therefore, the probability of observing \(y\) events of type \(B\) before \(r\) events of type \(A\) (with probability \(p\)) is

\(P(Y=y)=f(y)=\binom {y+r-1} k (1-p)^yp^r\), para \(y=0,1,...\)

When the distribution of \(Y\) is a negative binomial we write

\(Y\hookrightarrow NB(r,p)\)

Negative binomial distribution for events

A random variable with \(Y\hookrightarrow NB(r,p)\) has

  • mean: \(E(Y)= r\frac{1-p}{p}\)

  • variance: \(V(Y)= r\frac{1-p}{p^2}\)

Note that this is \(r\)-times those of the geometric distribution.

If we perform \(r\)-geometric experiments (composed on Bernoulli trials) the expectation for the sum the total amount \(B\) events is the same performing a single negative binomial experiment with tolerance \(r\).

Negative binomial distribution for events

  • A website has three servers.

  • One server operates at a time and only when a request fails another server is used.

  • If the probability of failure for a request is known to be \(p=0.0005\) then

  • what is the expected number of successful requests before the three computers fail?

Negative binomial distribution for events

This is a negative binomial process for the number of successes \(y\) \((y=0,1,2,...)\) before \(r=3\) and \(p=0.0005\) therefore

\(E(Y)=r\frac{1-p}{p}=3\frac{1-0.0005}{0.0005}=5997\)

  • Note that there are actually 6000 trials

Negative binomial distribution for events

What is the probability of dealing with at most with 5 successful requests before the system fails?

Recall the cumulative function distribution \(F(y)=P(Y\leq 5)\)

\(F(5)=P(Y\leq 5)=\Sigma_{y=0}^5 f(y)\)

\(=\sum_{y=0}^5\binom {y+2} y (0.9995)^y(0.0005)^y\)

\(=\binom {2} 0 (0.0005)^3 +\binom {3} 1 (0.9995)^1*(0.0005)^3\)

\(+\binom {4} 2 (0.9995)^2*(0.0005)^3 +\binom {5} 3 (0.9995)^3*(0.0005)^3\)

\(+\binom {6} 4 (0.9995)^4*(0.0005)^3 +\binom {7} 5 (0.9995)^5*(0.0005)^3\)

\(= 6.9\times 10^{-9}\)

Negative binomial distribution for trials

If we are interested in counting the number of trials before observing \(r\) events of type \(A\)

\((0,0,1,., 0,1,...0,1)=(B_1, B_2, A_3, ..., B_i,A_{i+1}, ... B_{y+r-1},A_{y+r})\)

we then count \(m=y+r\) trials, and the probability function for \(m\) trials before \(r\) evetns of type \(A\) is

\(P(M=m)=f(m)=\binom {m-1} {r-1} (1-p)^{m-r}p^r\), \(m=r,r+1,...\)

with

  • mean: \(E(M)= \frac{r}{p}\)

  • variance: \(V(M)= \frac{r(1-p)}{p^2}\)

Note that this is \(r\) times the mean and variance of the geometric distribution for events.

Hypergeometric distribution

  • Imagine we have a manufacturing process that for every \(850\) devices it produces per hour, \(50\) tend to be defective (\(5\%\)).

  • We don’t have time to count them all so we select \(100\) at random.

  • what is the probability that we choose \(5\) (\(5\%\)) defective devices?

Hypergeometric distribution

What do we know?

  • From a population of \(N\)
  • There are \(K\) that are not good (\(N-K\) are good)
  • A sample of \(n\) is chosen
  • In the sample, there are \(x\) taht are not good

what is the probability of observing a given value \(x\)?

Hypergeometric distribution

What do we know

  • From a population of \(N\)
  • There are \(K\) that are not good (\(N-K\) are good)

Let’s imagine we can mark each good devise \(B_1, ... B_K\) and each defective one \(A_1, ... A_ {N_K}\).

The population of devices is \(\{B_1, ... B_K, A_1, ... A_ {N_K} \}\)

Hypergeometric distribution

From the population \(\{B_1, ... B_ {N-K}, A_1, ... A_ {K} \}\) we choose a sample of size \(n\).

  • there are \(\binom N n\) of these samples

  • our particular sample

\((A_1, B_2, ... A_i,..B_{n})\)

has probability

\(P(A_1, B_2, ... A_i,..B_{n})=\frac{1}{\binom N n}\)

let’s assume that our sample has \(x\) bad devices (\(A\))

¿How many samples can we obtain with the same number \(x\) of bad devices?

Hypergeometric distribution

  • In how many ways we could get \(x\) different bad devises from a pool of \(K\)?

\[\binom K x\]

  • In how many ways we could get \(n-x\) different good devices from a pool of \(N-K\)?

\[\binom {N-K} {n-x}\]

All these samples have the same number of \(A\)s that our original sample \((A_1, B_2, ... A_i,..B_{n})\)

Hypergeometric distribution

Therefore the probability of obtaining \(x\) bad devises in a sample of \(n\) drawn from a population of \(N\) where \(K\) are bad is

\(P(X=k)=P(one\,sample) \times (Number\, of\, ways\, of\, obtaining\, x)\)

\(=\frac{1}{\binom N n}\binom K x \binom {N-K} {n-x}\)

where \(k \in \{\max(0, n+K-N), ... \min(K, n) \}\)

Hypergeometric distribution

Let’s think about the range of \(x\)

\(k \in \{\max(0, n+x-N), ... \min(K, n) \}\)

if there are few good devices and all get selected then there are at least \(n-(N-K)\) bad ones.

Hypergeometric distribution

  • Imagine we have a manufacturing process that for every 850 devices it produces per hour 50 tend to be defective (\(5\%\)).

  • We don’t have time to count them all so we select 100 at random.

  • what is the probability that we choose 5 defective devices?

Hypergeometric distribution

  • From a population of \(N=850\)

  • There are \(K=50\) that are not good (\(N-K=800\) are good)

  • A sample of \(n=100\) is chosen

The probability that in the sample there are \(k=5\) devices that are not good:

\(P(X=k) =\frac{1}{\binom N n}\binom K k \binom {N-K} {n-k}\)

\(P(X=5) =\frac{1}{\binom {850} {100}}\binom {50} {5} \binom {800} {95} = 0.17\,\, (17\%)\)

in R: choose(50, 5)*choose(800, 95)/choose(850, 100)

Hypergeometric distribution

Note that:

  • there are \(5.8\%\) of bad devices in the population (\(850\))
  • \(5\) bad devises in the sample (\(100\)) represent the \(5\%\)

Only \(\sim 20\%\) of the times, we would get exactly the same proportion of bad devices as in the population because the events are not independent

Hypergeometric distribution

These are not Bernoulli trials.

  • Independent Bernoulli trials will result if we inspect one device, drop it back, and take a new one (it can be the same).
  • In this case, we have sampling without replacement
  • At each draw of a device the sampling population change!

Hypergeometric distribution

If a random variable follows a hypergeometric mass probability function

\(P(X=x)=f(x)=\frac{1}{\binom N n}\binom K x \binom {N-K} {n-x}\)

\(x \in \{\max(0, n+K-N), ... \min(K, n) \}\)

It has

  • mean: \(E (X) = n * K / N = np\)

  • variance: \(V (X) = np (1-p) \frac {N-n} {N-1}}\)

when \(p=K/N\) is the proportion of events \(A\) in a population of size \(N\).

Hypergeometric distribution

Let’s compare the means and variances from a binomial variable

  • \(E_B(X)=np\) and variance \(V_B(X)= np(1-p)\)

and a Hypergeometric variable

  • \(E(X)=np\) and variance \(V(X)= np(1-p)\frac{N-n}{N-1}\)

The variance of the hypergeometric distribution is corrected for the sampling without replacement in a population with finite size.

The binomial distribution is derived from a sampling with replacement

The hipergoemetric distribution is derived from a sampling with no replacement, its variance is corrected from the efect of sampling a population with finite size.

Discrete probability models

We are building up more complex models from simple ones:

Uniform: Classical interpretation of probability
\(\downarrow\)
Bernoulli: Introduction of a parameter \(p\) (family of functions)
\(\downarrow\)
Binomial: Repetition of a random experiment (\(n\)-times Bernoulli trials)
\(\downarrow\)
Poisson: repetition of random experiment within an continuous interval (having no control on when/where to repeat the experiment).

Poisson distribution

Imagine that we are observing events that depend on time or distance intervals.

  • cars arriving at a traffic light
  • getting messages on your mobile phone
  • flaws occurring at random in a copper wire

Suppose that the events are outcomes of independent random experiments each appearing randomly on a continuous interval.

Poisson distribution

  • When we studied the binomial process we thought of repeating the flip of a coin \(n\) times.

  • We implicitly assumed that we controlled when the repetitions occurred.

  • Now we consider another layer of randomness: we do not control when the flip of the coin happens!

Poisson distribution

What is the probability of observing \(X\) events in an interval’s unit (time or distance)?

Imagine that some impurities in a copper wire deposit randomly along a wire

  • at each centimeter, you would count an average of \(\lambda=10/cm\).
  • divide the centimeter into micrometers (\(0.0001cm\))

Poisson distribution

micrometers are small enough so

  • either there is or there is not an impurity in each micrometer
  • each micrometer can be considered a Bernoulli trial

Poisson distribution

The probability of observing \(X\) impurities in \(n=10,000\mu\) (1cm) approximately follows a binomial distribution

\(P(X=x)=\binom n x (1-p)^{n-x}p^x\)

where \(p\) is the probability of finding an impurity in a micrometer.

Remember that \(E(X)=np\) so for \(\lambda=np\) (average number of impurities per 1cm), we can write

\(P(X=x)=\binom n x (1-\frac{\lambda}{n})^{n-x}\big(\frac{\lambda}{n}\big)^x\)

Poisson distribution

  • There could still be two flaws in a micrometer so we need to increase the partition of the wire (\(n\)).

  • The Bernoulli trials are only true in the limit (\(n \rightarrow \infty\)).

\(P(X=x)=\binom n x (1-\frac{\lambda}{n})^{n-x}\big(\frac{\lambda}{n}\big)^x\)

Where \(\lambda\) is constant because it is the density of flaws per centimeter, given by \(E(X)\).

Poisson distribution

\(P(X=x)=\binom n x (1-\frac{\lambda}{n})^{n-x} \big(\frac{\lambda}{n}\big)^x\)

in the limit (\(n \rightarrow \infty\))

  • \(\frac{1}{n^x}\binom n x =\frac{1}{n^x}\frac{n!}{x! (n-x)!}=\frac{(n-x)!(n-x+1)...(n-1)n}{n^x x! (n-x)!}=\frac{n(n-1)..(n-x+1)}{n^x x!} \rightarrow \frac{1}{x!}\)
  • \((1-\frac{\lambda}{n})^{n} \rightarrow e^{-\lambda}\) (definition of exponential)
  • \((1-\frac{\lambda}{n})^{-x} \rightarrow 1\)

Therefore \(P(X=x)= \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!}\)

Poisson distribution

Definition

Given

  • an interval in the real numbers
  • counts occur at random in the interval
  • the average number of counts on the interval is known (\(\lambda\))
  • if one can find a small regular partition of the interval such that each of them can be considered Bernoulli trials

Then…

Poisson distribution

Definition

The random experiment of counting across the interval is a Poisson process and the counts \(X\) follow the probability mass function
\(f(x)= \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!}, \lambda>0\)

Poisson distribution

for the Poisson distribution
\(f(x)=\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!}, \lambda>0\)

we have

  • mean \(E(X)= \lambda\)
  • variance \(V(X)= \lambda\)

Poisson distribution

The average number of radioactive particles hitting a Geiger counter is 2.3 seconds.

What is the probability of counting exactly 2 particles in a second?

\(f(x; \lambda)=\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!}, \lambda>0\)

\(f(2; \lambda=2.3)=\frac{e^{-2.3}2.3^2}{2!}=0.26, \lambda=2.3\, counts\)

Poisson distribution

The average number of radioactive particles hitting a Geiger counter is 2.3 counts each second.

What is the probability of counting exactly detecting 10 particles in 5 seconds?

If the probabilit of counts per 1 second is

\(f(x; \lambda_{1s})=\frac{e^{-\lambda_{1s}}\lambda_{1s}^x}{x!}, \lambda_{1s}=2.3\, counts\)

y \(E(X)=\lambda_{1s}\)

Then the avereage coutns per 5 seconds is

\(E(Y)=5\times \lambda_{1s}=\lambda_{5s}\) (we have to wait 5 units of times more)

The probability function fo \(Y\) is

\(f(y; \lambda_{5s})=\frac{e^{-\lambda_{5s}}\lambda_{5s}^y}{y!}, \lambda_{5s}=11.5 \, counts\)

therefore

\(f(10; \lambda_{5s})=\frac{e^{-11.5}11.5^{10}}{{10!}}=0.11, \lambda_{5s}=11.5 \,counts\)

Poisson distribution

What is the probability of at least one count in two seconds?

In general, the average of counts per \(\alpha\) seconds is

\(E(Z; \lambda_{\alpha})=\lambda = \alpha \times \lambda_{\alpha}\)

when \(\alpha=2\)

\(E(Z; \lambda_{2s})=\lambda_{2s} = 2 \lambda_{1s} =4.6 \, conteos\)

is the mean of the random variable \(Z\) that counts the number of particles that hit the detector each 2 seconds: \(Z \hookrightarrow Poiss(\lambda_ {2s})\) y

\(P(Z > 0)=1-F_{Pois}(0; \lambda_{2s})=1-f(0; \lambda_{2s})=1-e^{-4.6}=0.98 \nonumber\)
